TITLE: Invoking Other Functions with step.Invoke() in Go
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to use step.Invoke() to asynchronously call another Inngest function and handle the result. This method allows for reusing functionality and composing more complex workflows or map-reduce type jobs.
SOURCE: https://github.com/inngest/website/blob/main/pages/docs/learn/inngest-steps.mdx#2025-04-10_snippet_11

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import (
  "github.com/inngest/inngestgo"
  "github.com/inngest/inngestgo/errors"
  "github.com/inngest/inngestgo/step"
)

inngestgo.CreateFunction(
  &inngestgo.FunctionOpts{
    ID: "send-delayed-email",
  },
  inngestgo.EventTrigger("app/user.signup", nil),
  // handler function
  func(ctx context.Context, input inngestgo.Input) (any, error) {
    // Invoke another function and wait for its result
    result, err := step.Invoke[any](
      ctx,
      "invoke-email-function",
      step.InvokeOpts{
        FunctionID: "send-welcome-email",
        // Pass data to the invoked function
        Data: map[string]any{
          "user_id": input.Event.Data["user_id"],
          "email":   input.Event.Data["email"],
        },
        // Optional: Set a concurrency limit
        Concurrency: step.ConcurrencyOpts{
          Limit: 5,
          Key:   "user-{{event.data.user_id}}",
        },
      },
    )
    if err != nil {
      return nil, err
    }
    return result, nil
  },
)
```

