TITLE: Rust implementation of errors as values using Result type
DESCRIPTION: A Rust example demonstrating the Result type approach to error handling. Result is a wrapper type that contains either a successful value (Ok) or an error value (Err), forcing explicit error handling.
SOURCE: https://github.com/inngest/website/blob/main/content/blog/python-errors-as-values.mdx#2025-04-10_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: rust
CODE:
```
// Define a function that returns a Result with a User or an error string
fn get_user(user_id: &str) -> Result<Option<User>, &str> {
    match find_user_by_id(user_id) {
        Some(user) => Ok(Some(user)),
        None => Err("user not found"),
    }
}

fn rename_user(user_id: &str, name: String) -> Result<User, &str> {
    // Consume the function
    match get_user(user_id) {
        Ok(Some(mut user)) => {
            user.name = name;
            Ok(user)
        },
        Ok(None) => Err("user not found"),
        Err(e) => Err(e),
    }
}
```

